    <segment id="1" parent="21" relname="span">
I&apos;d like to respond to something Fuller said 2 days ago about the appl;ied
ethics model.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="19" relname="span">  I&apos;m not sure that it is all that clear to him,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="evidence"> as he tended
to dismiss it with associations like public relations and sophistry.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="22" relname="span">  

It may be the case that, say, physicians and surgeons turned to ethicists
as a response to crisis. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="14" relname="sequence"> But that doesn&apos;t mean that ethicists simply wait
around for practitioners to hand them a problem,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="14" relname="sequence"> and then seek some ;way
to smooth things over.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="16" relname="span">  some, but definitely not all, do this. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span"> But many
in the field have taken a critical stance f the sort SF would like to see
iin STS.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="concession">  For example, I may be wrong about this,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="antithesis"> but it was not doctors
who came to philosophers asking them how they could act less paternalistic-
ally.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span">  I think it was philosophers who were bringing traditional, perhaps
Kantian, concerns about the moral autonomy of human  beings to bear on 
a &quot;practical&quot; question.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="23" relname="span">

In your book, Steve, you argue theoretically against giving rhetoric a
bad name.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="antithesis">  But you continue to use it on the list in a way that 
contributes to its bad reputation!</segment>
